author: No BS Guy
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on January 28, 2018
review_content: Our family grew up together in some sort of Jenga haze where at every get together this was dragged out and we played for hours.Fast forward 15 years and I got this for my 3 year old (yeah, yeah, he doesn't have the manual dexterity or patience....Stop interrupting me) to pass that haze onto the next generation.Guess what, he loves Jenga!!  Just not in the ultra competitive, beer fueled way.  He views them as blocks, so we spend an hour or so each episode building stuff and knocking it down.Eventually we will start actually playing Jenga, but for now, his journey towards the haze of my youth is wonderful.Peace, No BS Guy
title: his journey towards the haze of my youth is wonderful. Peace

author: TEST
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on November 17, 2018
review_content: This is a really good game. It actually improves the focus of kids, because if you will lose the focus you may lose the game. The best part about it is, you can plaiit alone or with more players so you are not bound by number of players. I buyed it for my 8 years old son because he liked it so much. We have to actually remove each block at a time on your turn and make sure the tower should not loose the balance. Overall I like this game because you can spend hours playing this without getting bored as well you can finish it early if you have limited time. Overall worth it's price and good game.
title: Worth it's price

author: MrLikeke
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on March 26, 2018
review_content: The classic Jenga set brings back great memories growing up and playing with it as a youngster.  But I also remember back in the day of a sturdy clear plastic stacking sleeve. Just hope the current sleeve, which obviously didn’t meet my expectations, will last...the reason for mid 3-star rating. I bought the classic to pair it with my recent purchase of the colored wooden blocks of animal cartoons by Sun Top (Top Bright?) since the children’s set didn’t come with a stacking sleeve.  Nevertheless, I’m truly having fun with my grandkids and they love it as well and now I have a game to introduce to my senior friends. Why not offer a sturdier plastic stacking sleeve as an upgrade/accessory item?
title: Follow up review

author: Nicole
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on July 28, 2017
review_content: I bought these for an adult drinking game using google suggestions for each block, worked out well!
title: Five Stars

author: Kerry Summers-Valdez
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on January 14, 2019
review_content: Happy to see the wood pieces are still made of wood. That's about the only thing familiar you'll see from the last time you bought a Jenga game.The box is rectangle.  The Jenga tower is square. The box contains cardboard padding that clearly is intended to be discarded. So now what? Put the bricks in the box and watch them shift around. It's like a bag of chips puffed up to look fuller. But why?And where's the plastic half cube that used to come with the set so you can easily straighten the tower? Not included, apparently.
title: Not thrilled.

author: Joni
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on January 6, 2016
review_content: If somebody doesn't know what Jenga is about: it is a game where you build a tower out of wooden blocks (3 pieces per floor), and players are taking turns to remove blocks out of the tower. If the tower falls apart on your turn, you will lose the game. It is very simple and fun game.If you're looking for a game as described above, then you can't go wrong with this product. Amazon delivered it in timely fashion as usual, and the product is exactly what you would expect–a bunch of wooden blocks that you can use to build a tower. Also, this comes with game instructions and some kind of stacking aid made out of carton. I tossed the stacking aid to trash, since I find it to be much faster to build the tower by hand without the aid.In my opinion, the game is at its best when played with two people, but there's no limit of how many people can participate in the game. I would recommend using a stable table to play the game on, but a dangling Ikea table (or equivalent) surely adds some challenge.In a good company this game is much more fun than any video game on the market, making it a bargain at less than $10. This game will also work anywhere with decent gravity–as long as you are able to find a stable surface. In conclusion, I would recommend Jenga to anyone living on a planet that has a sufficient gravitational force to hold the tower together on the surface, which includes all the areas to which Amazon.com delivers.
title: No HDMI Cable Required

author: Bo Duke
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on January 2, 2019
review_content: Purchased this directly from Amazon, and it came new and wrapped in clear plastic.  The inside block stack was also wrapped in plastic, which preserves the blocks until opening.  The blocks are not painted, which allows them to stay together and the game to proceed normally without being shortened by premature slippage. The cardboard box is rectangular, and might serve as a storage mechanism for the blocks for awhile, but I suspect it will not last for that purpose.  I'd prefer a storage bag, like several of the knock-offs that are marketed here have, but a bag might be found elsewhere.
title: Well-made classic, but I wish it came with a bag

author: Nicholas Ramsey
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on June 8, 2016
review_content: For the cost of this game, for under 15 dollars, you really can't beat the amount of fun and suspense that it delivers. My fiancé and all of my friends love this game very much; as well as my parents which tells you that all generations love this game. This is probably one of the best "board games" there are around; if you have little kids this would definitely teach hand eye coordination. Definitely durable given the amount of times the tiles have came crashing down going every which way. This game has suspense with no real danger, appeals to all ages, is simple to play, and lasts forever. You can still play it on a coffee table or dining room table, you don't need to clear a place on the floor. One thing I would suggest is changing the box size, you would think that the box would be the exact shape of the game so the pieces aren't rattling around in the box.  All in all; it's a great game for a great price that you can't beat. Definitely a must buy to keep in your home for a rainy day or for a family game night.
title: you really can't beat the amount of fun and suspense that it delivers

author: CJ
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on March 25, 2018
review_content: Classic toy which provides fun for everyone. Really enjoyed reliving a game from the past. Pieces all appear uniform although I'm pretty sure the quality of the blocks are not as good as the original ones that were made. I'm sure these are lighter.The only other gripe is the very cheap cardboard guide that comes along with the game to assist you in rebuilding the tower once it's been toppled. I'd pay more if there was a better device to assist in building the tower again.Hours of fun that even our 4 year old was able to fully participate in. A non electronic game that holds your attention span..... amazing !
title: Great fun which brings back memories

author: James Cortina
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on August 31, 2016
review_content: This toy is extremely durable (how can you really break those small blocks of wood?), it's incredibly flexible as a toy. My family and I plays this game for hours. When my daughter plays it alone, she stays occupied with the game -- playing it alone, stacking and re-stacking the blocks, creating houses and encampments as if the pieces were designed as building blocks.As an adult, I don't enjoy card games or board games much, but I still appreciate having this game around the house. It's a game you can play with just about anyone, and although it does take some concentration when you're the one pulling out that precarious block, you can still converse and cavort while playing (as long as you've got the game on a stable surface!).Jenga also helps teach hand-eye coordination, precision, patience, forethought ("what will happen if I pull out this block?"), and just a bit of physics -- some of the blocks are rougher, some are smoother, so friction comes into play.I highly recommend this game to everyone, regardless of age!
title: Love it

author: ***ME***
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on October 16, 2016
review_content: This was just as expected. I was originally looking for a colored jenga set for a shower, but they were all double/triple the price so I bought this plain one and just painted the edges with cheap craft paint. See attached picture.
title: Just As Exptected- thanks!

author: Kalatraza
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on February 2, 2016
review_content: This one is the real thing -- Jenga as I remember playing it as a kid. (We'll assume my memory is still intact.) Just a box full of wood sticks, some of which aren't finished all that well and some not-so-great instructions. It's possible that this game was more of a Midwestern thing because people don't always know what I'm talking about when I mention my wish to build a gigantic version in the backyard.Don't let that be your or your children's loss or your grandchildren's. My brother, sister, and I played this game rather peacefully for at least an hour at a time. My mom would play it with us. Occasionally even my dad, and he hates games. It's a great solo toy, too, for the little ones who like to build. And while you could hide those markers, what will be more fun in 20 years? A perfect vintage Jenga set? Or one that your children "decorated" as toddlers? Maybe you should just put some nice markers in your cart while you're at it.I'm all nostalgic about this one, but more than many games and toys of my childhood, I believe this one is still worth playing (which is why I now have my own set). You don't plug it in. It doesn't have any lights, bells, buzzers, or whistles. There's no robot, no artificial intelligence, and not a darn thing anyone can control with their smartphone. It does have suspense, and if you're not paying attention, you do miss all the fun.
title: An excellent game from my childhood. Still fun, no wifi required.

author: Fenicky Female
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on March 22, 2017
review_content: My 6 year old grandson requested this for Christmas and it had to be the "Classic Jenga." The family played and we all loved it.  This classic game never gets old.  My family played in teams, my son and his girlfriend, whom was having dinner with the family for the first time versus my daughter and her husband.  Couple against couple sounds about right?  Not according to my grandson. They had to switch it up.  "Brother and sister versus the others", lol. His words not mine, smiles.  He was the self delegated "score keeper and ref",  He had more fun rooting for everyone as a individuals and a team. He even made his own handwritten awards to give out. This was perfect addition for more  family bonding, an ice breaker, as well as competition with love, smiles. Thanks, Ms. Scott for your invention.
title: Family LOVED IT!

author: J Zimmer
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on September 24, 2017
review_content: Although I can't say it is entirely false advertising, using the word GIANT in bolder letters implies BIG, LARGE, OVERSIZED.  Nope.  The blocks are the size of blocks found in a nice wood building block set. See Melissa & Doug  Solid Wood Building Blocks w/ Wooden Tray (60 Ct) for $59.00.  BIG gripe is the cost of larger Jenga blocks that only stack 3 feet high.  Seventy-five dollars ($75.00) is slightly pretentious, and the pictures are slightly misleading.  However, it works like Smaller version Jenga,and my kids in play therapy get a kick out of it when it crashes.  The box is sturdy enough for storing the blocks.  Just don't get too excited, not a hot deal.
title: Be careful reading the description and Size

author: Hello Minnie
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on February 4, 2016
review_content: I got this game for my daughter for Christmas. It was exactly what I was expecting. My only complaint is that the box is much bigger than the game pieces, it would make storing it and putting it away much easier if the box were the same size, as it is it's nearly impossible to put away neatly. I gave up and put all the pieces in a ziplock bag. Not ideal and it's a pain to store it that way in our game cupboard but since the tower kept falling over and messing up in the box it was the easiest solution.Aside from that it's the classic Jenga we all love! My daughter loves it and it's a fun (albeit noisy!!) addition to our Family Game Night tradition. The instructions were easy to figure out and all of my kids have proved able to play it just fine. This is a must have in any Family Game cupboard!
title: Box is too big for the tower, makes putting it away neatly impossible.

author: Gina Central
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on April 27, 2016
review_content: A fun classic game for the whole family. Except cats.... cats hate Jenga. I've seen a few that like it but they are rare. As soon as the tower falls they run up the wall and out the door. Its not rocket science which is what makes it fun. You remove a block and put it on the top and the next player goes. You can learn a lot about a person and the way they play Jenga. I bet you never knew Nana was such a cut throat. Its a pretty compact game to take on a family trip to not a ton so space. Not going to be an option in the car thought so road trips are out.
title: Great fun for the whole family.

author: Z. YU
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on July 14, 2015
review_content: If you are really into this game, you would care about the quality of the wood. Because if the wood is made of cheap compressed plywood or something, instead of dense hard wood, it would make a big difference when you try to pull a piece in the stack. The friction between woods will be enough to overcome the weight of the structure on top, thus causing the whole thing collapse more easily.Other than that, overall this is a good product given its price. I would recommend this product if you are a casual player and only play it sometimes as one of the many game you have handy.
title: It works, but cheaply made

author: Sarah
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on March 4, 2020
review_content: So I bought this for a friends Christmas gift so the next time the two of us and a couple of our other friends got together we could play this. Yesterday we finally played this game and I give this five stars for the fun we had and the panic inducing anxiety we got from the sheer fact that we played some risky moves and made the structure unstable,but yet still stable and had not fallen over yet. When my one friend finally knocked it over and released us from our anxious, panic filled, sweat filled mood,we all felt a sense of relief as we started again. The second game was even more anxiety inducing as I pulled a "risky" move that one would call miraculous almost and pure genius. This game will keep you away from your phone and off social media. This game will give you and your friends the best memories and quality time well spent. This game will also make those prone to sweating sweat a decent amount. Don't worry you will recover. Thank you Jenga for giving my friends and I a fun filled 2 hours of sheer fun torture. I highly recommend this for you and your family and friends and if you have any enemies, I recommend you play this with them and make it as challenging as possible to not knock the blocks over.
title: Be prepared to have some anxiety playing this.

author: o_happy_home
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on March 1, 2019
review_content: Always a fun game but now with memories attached.  We used this at our wedding in place of a guest book.  Everyone just signed a jenga piece.  Now we play and we can read all the notes and guest who came to our special day!
title: We used in place of guest book at our wedding.

author: Zhill
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on June 17, 2019
review_content: Update : I have bought 2 more sets of Jenga since the original review. During this lockdown, other than spending time in playing the traditional game, my child also loves using the Jenga blocks to construct endless structures big and small for her dolls. She loves themMore than her Legos. I reiterate that the blocks are beautifully made ( I learnt from India) and lightweight and never had any splinters or sharp edges till date. It’s just a solidly entertaining game which can be used in multiple ways. One of my best purchased toys on Amazon.I bought this as a gift for my 9 year old nephew who is a blocks enthusiast. I got it for just under 8$ and didn’t expect the quality to be so good. The blocks are well made from wood and have no chips or splinters at the edges. They make for loads of fun for adults or kids and helps in concentration and strategy. My nephew was more than pleased and I liked the set so much I bought one for myself and play with my 4 year old who’s loving it too. So worth the price and highly recommendable.
title: Super fun Amazing Quality

author: Nathan V. Packer
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on December 27, 2019
review_content: Ok, as far as the game goes, it's Jenga, the blocks are fine quality, 5 stars there.  But as other reviews have stated, the packaging sucks, and I give it 3 stars.  For an overall rating of 4 stars. The problem comes when you want to store the blocks.  You have two trains of thought here.  Save the time of stacking them nicely when you are done, by just throwing them all in the box, and then set them up when you want to play next, OR stack them neatly in the box when you're done, so you don't have to set them up when you want to play next, because you can just slide them out of the box, ready to play.  Either of those options means you only have to stack them nicely once.You can't do EITHER with this packaging.  We tried the first scenario, just throwing them all in the over-sized rectangular box, thinking that must be why it's bigger, so it can accommodate all of the blocks when they're not stacked up nicely.  NOPE.  They won't fit if you just throw them all in.  Ok, not a problem, we'll just stack them neatly in the cardboard corner guide they give you and put them in.  While that will allow you to fit all the blocks in the box, there is nothing inside to hold them together, so they all fall apart anyway as soon as you move the box to a shelf and you have to set them up again when you want to play again!  So when you put them away, you have to stack them nicely, and then when you want to play, you have to stack them AGAIN before playing.  I mean you could solve this by either 1. Make the box square, so the blocks don't come apart in the box, or 2. Make the box big enough to accommodate all the blocks when they are just thrown in randomly.  There could be a 3rd option, which would be to just get a big gallon size ziplock bag, they might all fit in there.  However, then you have no place to store the cardboard sleeve which acts as a guide when setting them up.  You just can't win. Packaging fail.TL;DR The game is fine, but putting them away and setting them up sucks purely because of the packaging.Rant over.
title: Game, 5star, Packaging 3

author: Kindle Customer
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on December 15, 2019
review_content: This is a classic game that I loved as a kid and bought for my daughter for Christmas.  I want to make others aware, since there was no warning on the description (sometmes there is, but for this item there was not) there was no outer box, the toy was just shipped so that you see what it is.  I would recommend checked the "this is a gift" option if you need to keep the contents hidden. My daughter was right there when I brought it in. I think I managed to keep it out of her sight.  :-(.  however, it makes for an awkward Santa gift when there i an Amazon label attached. lol. Also it was raining and the box was left on my doorstep in the rain.  The box was soggy, but hopefully the contents are ok, I couldn't even check.
title: jenga game

author: Elizabeth
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on December 29, 2018
review_content: So we love Jenga in our house and wanted a new set after we lost some of the other pieces. Oddly, however, this comes in a box that is not the same size as the game so you can't easily store it stacked up in the box. And the thing that is supposed to be used to keep it in shape in between games and to set it up right is no longer hard plastic but cheap cardboard, so it is not going to last very long (with a house full of kids) so there won't be an easy way to re-set the game up without the thing that keeps it i the right shape. Our old Jenga game had a nice plastic thing to keep the shape of the game and then a box that was the size of the game so it could be easily stored in the box in between games. For a game with a million pieces, it makes no sense to not think about how people will store it and set it up. I'm sure it is a cost-saving thing and marketing thing, but if you can buy one with a smaller box so you can easily store it and keep its shape in between games. Of course the game is great as always.
title: Great game, poor packaging

author: KL
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on January 2, 2020
review_content: My son asked for Jenga for Christmas, and he's pleased with his new game. I think the wood blocks themselves are quality with smooth, flat surfaces and square edges. However, I expected to be able to stack the tower back into the box when the game is not in use. The description says it includes a stacking sleeve--which I didn't see the kids open the game so I don't know exactly what was in the rectangular retail package but packaging/stacking sleeve is lacking in my opinion. There is nothing to help keep the tower square as you stack the blocks into shape. And then you either dump them back into the rectangle-shaped retail package and risk them not all fitting as they pile up haphazardly, or you take the time to stack them knowing the stack won't survive into the correct shape next time you take the blocks out of the package to play. So, I guess that lends itself to the cheaper price.
title: Wood Blocks are Good--But NO Stacking Assistance

author: Michelle
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on June 30, 2020
review_content: I love this game. We've gotten pretty good and most of our games end in stalemates where there are no available moves. We can keep playing by allowing two hands and attempting to restructure the tower so we can pull more blocks. We actually ended up just buying a second game and making the initial tower taller.I will agree with others that the boxes are stupid as all he--. I don't know why its a rectangle so the blocks don't fit without a struggle to center it. The cardboard cutouts used to fill in the spaces are flimsy and move around. It's so dumb so I took a star off for whatever twit designed the packaging.
title: Always loved Jenga

author: Chris Tyrrell
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on February 25, 2020
review_content: Ugh.  It keeps falling over!!!  What a defective solid block of wood!Jenga must be Spanish for unsturdy disappointment
title: Blockhead

author: Jim
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on June 11, 2019
review_content: What can you say about a box full of wooden blocks?  They're exactly what you would expect.  One thing I will say - I seem to remember years ago, when Jenga first came out, they gave you a nice plastic thingy that you could use to square up and straighten the stack of blocks.  Now, it's just a cheap piece of thin cardboard.  Not a big deal - you really don't even need it - but it is a change from before.  Anyway, it's still a fun game.
title: It's classic Jenga

author: valentineslover
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on August 1, 2016
review_content: This box is rectangular, not square like the old ones so it takes some finagling to get the blocks back in. It's Jenga all right...simple as it can be. We took a permanent marker and wrote questions and phrases to complete on the blocks.."What is your favorite color?" "What do you want to be when you grow up?" "If you could go anywhere on vacation, where would you go?" You can find questions and phrases all over the internet and you can skip if you don't feel comfortable answering something. We opted to do this because it takes a relatively short and detached game to another level--it really becomes a conversation and you get to know people better, even your ow family.
title: Classic game and you can make it your own

author: Simone Y. Regan MSW,CSW
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on September 26, 2019
review_content: As a brand new therapist, I've found that this game (especially with little open ended get to know you questions written on each piece) is fantastic for ice-breaking visits with new clients. It allows for something to do with hands,  questions that can be ignored or used as either person feels like, and a subtle way to break up the awkwardness with getting to know you visits. This particular set is simple enough, and sturdy enough to be used as building blocks, domino tipping or as the game is meant to be played and it was affordable enough to get one for myself and my closest friend in gradschool with me. <3  love this product.
title: Jenga for therapists!

author: Amazon Customer
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on June 12, 2016
review_content: The Classic Jenga has turned into cheap junk. The "hardwood" feels more like styrofoam, the pieces are all slightly asymmetrical, and the wood burned logos are faded and inconsistent.How have they managed to mess up blocks? What happened here? My childhood is let down.
title: Lost Quality Over the Years

author: Janet Butterfield
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on February 13, 2019
review_content: I had this game many years ago and it came with a heavy plastic sleeve for stacking. this one is as funky as they get. You have to keep all parts of the packaging if you want to put it away neatly, which never works. Rectangle box for square objects, lol! We learned this simple geometry when we were kids, it doesn't work Hasbro! I love the game but the manufacturer got really cheap this time around!
title: Plastic stacking sleeve, funky

author: Customer
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on February 1, 2018
review_content: Jenga is a classic. Purchased three of these to gift to friends, it's the ultimate housewarming gift, or even fitting to take to a dinner party.It's the perfect gift, but there is a caveat. There is a strange wood smell that we noticed on all the sets. Some of the blocks also don't fit perfectly together. Might not be a big deal, but if the misfit blocks happen to be in a few crucial junctures when playing, the Jenga tower will be even more imbalanced than it should be. Some might see this as a feature. What else do you expect for $10 or so?
title: Perfect for dinner parties, adults & kids alike

author: Jennifer
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on April 24, 2020
review_content: There is nothing classic about this. The packaging on the updated version is completely insane and makes absolutely no sense. The older version has a normal box to put the pieces away in, and they just slide right out. The new version is some complicated piece of trash filled with a bunch of extra cardboard pieces. Why is that? Because whoever designed this new version decided to make the box bigger than the pieces, so now there’s a bunch of unnecessary steps to put the damn thing away.  Idiots. Don’t fix something that’s not broken!
title: Game is the same but the packaging is trash

author: Brandy Bishop
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on January 3, 2020
review_content: After 38 years TV is becoming boring so I decided to make a change. The change was do away with television every so often and Play a game. Wasn't sure what game the kids would actually like but Jenga was the win. It's easy for my five year old all the way up to my 43 year old big kid (my husband). This is a game we all get excited about. It's down to the steady pull and which one to take out. Don't be the shaky bottom pull or you could just be JENGA.
title: Who will build the highest and who will, JENGA

author: Jane Brown
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on April 15, 2020
review_content: We have this game set up in our office breakroom.  Everyone takes a turn while getting coffee/lunch.  We all laugh when we hear it crash on the countertop.  I've bought another game for our weekend camping.  Sturdy game for a picnic table and great for all ages.
title: Fun!

author: Amazon Customer
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on January 27, 2020
review_content: its hard to find a game easy enough for the 6 and under crowd that isnt boring for the adults but this one is a classic and my daughter thinks it is so much fun she also plays blocks with it building towers.  here i was spending hundreds on christmas and what do you know this inexpensive board game takes the cake as one of her favorite gifts i think it good for concentrations as well she is a smart little girl so she wins half the time leaving the tower toppling down on the rest of us it fun to see you dont have to spend a lot to have a good time.
title: great family game like always

author: A. Graham
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on June 15, 2020
review_content: Never owned this game before, but I’ve played it.  Thought it would be a good diversion for the spouse and myself during quarantine.  Something non-electronic that we can do together.  I was pleased with the outcome.  A few evenings of real togetherness and laughs.
title: Family Fun if you’re looking for a diversion that will make you laugh

author: Ms. Muse
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on June 4, 2020
review_content: I'm pretty sure we've all played this game. It's a lot of fun and can be played with 1 or 2 people which is great these days. The blocks are very sturdy and durable ready to last for years. My only complaint is that they used to come in a metal tin which made stacking them back and resetting for game quick and easy. These only have a cardboard shelf that you stack them on and then have to carefully slide out to reset. Still not bad.
title: Classic Game

author: Justyn VdP
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on June 14, 2018
review_content: It's Jenga... it's awesome. It came on time. It was exactly what I expected. Now, I do think my kid was trying to cheat when we played, but that's not Jenga's fault. My kid also really liked building house after our game. When I recommend this game? You bet. It's fun. The instructions are on the side. You can get stricter with the rules if you wanted to. And if you decide you don't want to play anymore? Build a fortress with the blocks.
title: it's awesome. It came on time

author: Thomas
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on December 15, 2019
review_content: Decent product. Does the job for what I wanted but the pieces do feel slightly poor in quality. The wooden pieces feels a little fake compared to my past experiences with the game, so it’s not as satisfying to play with. The game box has some extra space when the tower is in the box, so it moves around inside, not ideal.
title: Decent, quality seems slightly poor

author: PawPawRon
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on December 8, 2020
review_content: My Wife suggested we buy this game to have on hand when our Granddaughters visit as a means of getting them to put their electronic devices down for a short time and doing something that requires hands on activity.This appears to be a great value for the cost and one that does not take up a lot of space to store and one that both our Granddaughters have said they find to be lots of fun.
title: A Great Way To Get Your Grandchildren Off Their Electronic Devices

author: Mom Prime
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on July 1, 2019
review_content: We received the product in time but some of the blocks had sticky glue on them.
title: Great game but product was defective.

author: Ruth A. Vokac
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on January 15, 2017
review_content: From some Amazon reviews that said kids had to spend more time stacking blocks than playing the game, I was somewhat doubtful about ordering Jenga.  But because the game was reasonably priced, I decided to try it.  I bought two for 6 year old grandchildren in different families.  I played the first game with each of them. None of us had played Jenga before.  Yet we all found it fun and challenging.  Both kids could determine which blocks were best to remove, and they had the dexterity to play well.  I am glad I took a chance!
title: Fun game!!

author: Bunge
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on December 28, 2019
review_content: This is perfect to play with lots of different ages. My youngest kiddos will play by building things with the blocks and my older ones will play by the rules.  Where it's simple to play/follow, it's a great game for them. I wish there was a case or something to keep all the pieces together, but I knew there wasn't going to be so I put them in a ziplock bag and that's worked so far.  Great price too!
title: Great Game for All Ages

author: Martin
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on January 1, 2015
review_content: Jenga used to come with a plastic jig/template that allowed you to make a nice tight tower and thus play a fair game. They have replaced it with a piece of cardboard that is totally useless and really just packaging. Given how long the game has included it, I consider removing it akin to cheating me. While I don't think I have much standing to return it, I think it is a petty move and I have lost respect for the Hasbro because of it.
title: No longer includes critical plastic piece to make the tower

author: Poiuytrew.q
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on August 24, 2019
review_content: Basically what I ordered. I haven't seen the new Jenga, just the one I had in the 90's. What I appreciated about the old one was that there was this plastic cover so you could easily make the tower for the next game if you stacked it in the box. This box takes up space, there considerable space on the side, which I assume is because most people just want to throw the Jenga pieces in the box because they're LAZY.I will probably make a wooden box to store them, because I have limited storage on my bookshelves.
title: Classic Jenga

author: Joe
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on September 5, 2017
review_content: Bigger is better with Jenga!  We had had the standard size game for many years, but the giant version is a lot more fun. But don't buy from Amazon if you plan to store the game in the manufacturer's box. They just apply shipping labels and send without additional packaging. Unacceptable!!
title: Fun game -- buy somewhere else!

author: Richard R
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on June 8, 2014
review_content: I am familiar with Jenga, I had a game for a very long time. The box had an exterior flap with instructions, a plastic sleeve for help in stacking and keeping pieces from falling out of the "Window" of the box when the pieces were put inside the box. The interior of the box I was familiar with, helped in that once you stacked the Jenga game with the sleeve, and put it away, it was ready to go next time you were ready to play. Just open the box, gently tip it upside down, remove the box, and the game is stacked and ready to go!This new box, with a copyright of 2012, is wider than the stacked Jenga blocks. Wider, meaning that the box is rectangular. You can no longer stack the blocks, and have them put away, ready to go for next time.When the box arrived to me from Amazon, I had immediate dread when I saw how wide the box was, when I grabbed the box, the edges started to cave in, because there was nothing but dead space on the sides of the box. I was baffled as to why Jenga would be stacked inside with all this dead space. Is this for real?It seems now, that Hasbro doesn't want you to put away the game nicely anymore, rather just throw all the blocks in the box, loose, nothing neat. Then, pretty much anytime you grab the flimsy exterior box, you end up caving it in a bit.The cardboard sleeve replaces the plastic sleeve, and while of a decent thickness of cardboard, it's a definite step-down from the plastic sleeve.I also don't know why Hasbro switched to a box much large than the stacked contents. Most people I know, and knew of, with Jenga had no problems stacking the game pieces and putting them away. Never heard any complaints out of anyone during all these years with Jenga, except when someone accidentally sat on the plastic stacking sleeve that was sitting on a sofa (Clear, easy to miss) and damaged it.My advice is, that if you are familiar with the "old" way Jenga was stacked, and packed away, find an older set and buy that. They're out there.
title: The new box is horrible

author: Joanne dang
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on December 22, 2019
review_content: Classic game, great for all ages but hilarious with kids. I recently bought this again for a coworker's kid who is 4 and is now able to understand the mechanics of simple games like this and I can just imagine him cracking up laughing every time the tower tumbles. P.S. for a twist, write rules on each jenga piece so that whenever the block is pulled out, the action has to be taken by the player who pulled it.
title: Classic game

author: Linda
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on September 7, 2016
review_content: Very fun. I love this game. We have it setup in the games area of our outdoor Gluten Free Café and plan to take it on our camping trip! All ages love it! Young & Old!

author: Valdiviez
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on May 31, 2019
review_content: This game is a classic and great for kids and adults alike. review_content: It's Jenga (a classic) so there's not much to say. Fun for every age, even my 3 year old can play. My only complaint is that they have changed the design of the box from when I was younger. The box use to be square so you could put them away neatly and then when you wanted to play again you just tipped the box over and the blocks came out ready to play. Now the box is rectangular so now you just have to toss and the blocks in when done and when you want to get it back out you have to completely reset it up. I know it's not really that big of a deal 😀 but I just can't understand why they would have changed it when it worked so well before.

author: Matt Dobson
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on April 1, 2016
review_content: They say certain things are like gateway drugs.. Well i found this to be true with Jenga..It all starts in the year 2000. It was New Years Eve, and i had been invited to a friends house to celebrate the new year. The night started off normal with drinks, food, and a few good laughs and joke. Then it all began... One of the guys at the party asked if we were interested in playing "a game". We all agreed it could be fun, and gathered around the kitchen table. As he placed his backpack on the table I swore i saw a flash of light shining through the zipper. He pulled a dusty old box out, and i could barely make out the lettering J-E-N-G-A.I don't remember much after the wood blocks were setup.. My mind races as i think back to that night.. blackness overcomes my thoughts, with flashbacks filling my memory. My eyes glaze over as i start to remember.  Chanting.. JENGA, JENGA, JENGA, someone running around without any cloths on, the house being set on fire. When i ask my friends what happened that night no one seems to remember. No one remember HIS NAME.Since that night I could never break away from the game. I tried counseling, i tried rehab, but nothing breaks me free. Every second of the day I'm thinking about the block I should of pulled, or the strategies of center block versus end blocks. I've lost my wife, my home, and my job due to these wood demons. I've entered into underground tournaments and lost everything I've ever worked for.But there is good in everything. With the life lessons obtained from this game I was able to escape prison. As I pulled blocks and bricks I had focus that none of the other prisoners had ever seen. I worked with precision and accuracy, allowing myself to escape with the wall caving in on the chasing guards. Three of the guards died, but they can blame that on Jenga.. not me.. It's been almost two years since i've escaped, and I haven't touched the game since.Please pray that I can overcome this madness. My dreams and nightmares revolve around Jenga, and i just hope one day I'll be able to break free.
title: Life of Jenga, by Matt Dobson

author: Brendan C.
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on January 20, 2016
review_content: So, how do you give a box of blocks a review of two stars?  If you are judging just the blocks it is easily a five star product.  They are uniform, feel good quality, and the price is right.  The blocks are great.  The packaging is the issue.  Back in the 90s when you bought this the box was the size of the tower and you got a nice plastic sleeve to line things up.  It was durable and lasted a long while.  The new packaging the box is about two inches wider then the stack and the sleeve is cardboard, THIN cardboard.  And if it is messed up (really easy to do) then the two little cardboard blocks will not hold the stack up in the packaging.  Basically they took a very functional and durable packaging and made it stupid and cheap for no reason as the cost of redesigning the packaging had to out weigh the production cost of the old packaging.
title: Why change what works?

author: Mic
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on June 6, 2015
review_content: Ok, I'm a child of the 80s and I grew up playing this game.  Let it suffice to say I know my way around a Jenga box.  Be aware of two slightly disappointing things in this packaged version:1) The box itself is a rectangle shape, which makes NO sense to me, given the square design of the block tower.  The extra inch and a half of space on the side will surely lead to tipping, shifting, and tumbling of your carefully assembled tower when you put this away on the game shelf.  Alternately, you can attempt to reinsert the included cardboard sheath every single time you finish playing, which, again, makes me ask WHY DID YOU MAKE THE BOX RECTANGULAR  IN THE FIRST PLACE?! This box redesign is terrible.  Totally counterproductive.2) While there technically is a straightening sleeve that squares up your tower, it is made of very thin cardboard, and therefore sucks.  See the attached picture for reference - it speaks for itself.  Wait, you might say.... All I see is a piece of paper surrounding the Jenga blocks.  Where is the sleeve?  Your eyes aren't deceiving you.  That IS the sleeve.  The good old Jenga game of yesteryear came with a nice sturdy clear plastic sleeve that had a floor or ceiling (depending on your perspective) and two walls so you could build your tower into it and flip it over for the perfectly assembled and straightened tower.  It was the Jenga equivalent of a billiard triangle.  I have very little confidence in the ability and longevity of this flimsy cardboard imposter.  I might actually just go on eBay to look for a real plastic Jenga stacking sleeve.In summation, the blocks are fine, the game is still the same, but it's obvious Hasbro has cut some major corners in the production and packaging department.  Bring back the original design and square box!!!
title: The blocks are great, the box and straightening tool are NOT.

I like how you can play it by yourself or with friends. I'm a little worried though about a few things. I don't really like the shape of this box either for when you want to put it up, it doesn't feel big enough. author: Yuko Yoshimura
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on September 3, 2014
review_content: I was laughing, watching Ellen at "The Ellen Show" playing a gigantic JENGA with her guest. It's so fun to watch people playing Jenga.And here I am, playing Jenga with my 8 year old and 10 year old daughters. I like that little bit of thrill trying to pull one block out, and carefully stack it on the top. And no matter who wins or loses, everyone can't help laughing at the end when one player crash the blocks.You don't need to understand English to play Jenga. That is great for me because I have many friends from Japan who visit me with their kids who doesn't speak English at all. When Japanese friends come over, my kids can play Jenga together, and they can all have a great time!! Like I mentioned in my "Connect 4" review, classic games such as Jenga and Connect 4 are wonderful tools to interact with friends who don't speak the same language.Jenga is definitely one of the best classic family game!
title: Awesome classic game for all ages and all nationalities!

author: Kelsy
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on October 1, 2015
review_content: In Seal Beach, I had accidentally (yes, it was an accident) stolen the Jenga from a great bar (Clancy's).  I was a bit intoxicated, and so were my friends.  We were in port for a week, and, of course, the last night there, we were just sliding the Jenga blocks down the table into my purse.  I forgot about them until the next day, when I went to clean up my rack before quarters and heard wood clanging around in my purse.  We were pulling out that morning, though, so I couldn't return it.  I purchased this and mailed it to Clancy's with an apology letter.  I did have a friend whose ship pulled into Seal Beach the next week, and he had said he talked to the owner and they actually appreciated it, so that made me feel better.Sorry, Clancy's.
title: it was an accident) stolen the Jenga from a great bar (Clancy's)

date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on March 29, 2015
review_content: It's your typical quality Jenga game, BUT, the box is stupid. For some reason they decided to change their square box into a rectangle box. It's difficult getting back into the box because you have to fit it into the square cardboard cut out in the bottom all while trying to keep the pieces in the two-sided sleeve. It's a stupid box design for a game that is square. There's is absolutely no point in it being a rectangle other than to give them more area to put words and pictures on the box. I think I saw that there is a special edition that comes with a wood box inside. I would get that if I couldn't find a Jenga that comes in a square cardboard box.

author: In My Opinion
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on December 14, 2019
review_content: I hadn't played Jenga in decades, but recently got this to play with my kids. The description recommends age 8+ but my children are 7 and 5. It's always fun to introduce them to the games from my youth and find that kids today enjoy playing as much as kids from yesteryear.We don't play strictly by the rules at their age. They are allowed to use both hands and stabilize the tower as they pull out blocks. In addition to creating quality family time, it also teaches them about balance and making strategic decisions. And when the game is over, they can stack the blocks in "just for fun" ways.All these years later, Jenga is still a great game.
title: Still a great game

author: Ginni Olivia
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on June 4, 2013
review_content: For the cost of this game (under $15) you really can't beat the amount of fun it delivers. My three kids (ages 4 thru 7) ALL love it (and trust me, there's no other game they ALL love) and my husband and I also love it - which sort of tells you that it spans generations. Frankly, this is one of the only games I can think of out there that is fun AND appropriate for multiple generations (UNO is another one). Try explaining to a 4 year old why she can't play trivial pursuit or convincing an adult to play operation for the 16th time and you'll see why having a multi-generation-appropriate game is so important. Mine also came with a neat little stacker, so that little hands can stack up all the blocks themselves before the game starts. It's great for building hand/eye coordination in little kids and is suprisingly durable given the number of times we've all made those blocks come crashing down!
title: Great game!

author: Jani
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on May 5, 2019
review_content: No matter the age group that's using these jenga blocks, you can DEFINITELY make it fun for EVERYONE. I will say that making it fun for everyone means buying more than one set, lol.During adult games nights, you can have a set with blocks saying what the puller has to do or make a teammate do. Yes, it get WILD, lol.During children game nights, keep the blocks more PG-13 and kid friendly.During a more elder game night, keep the blocks easy going and fun.You will have a great time coming up with the ideas.
title: YOU CAN CREATE THE FUN

author: time2shop
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on June 13, 2016
review_content: I had played this game countless times at friend's parties and was always amazed at how much of an adrenaline rush it could be! When you start to see the tower sway as you are lightly tapping one of the pieces and start holding your breath because you fear that the air might knock it down, you know you're hooked! I've enjoyed this with kids and adults alike and it is one of those games that everyone can participate in and be on equal levels. The pieces are sturdy and well made, the price is incredibly reasonable, and the shipping is super fast. Also, it is one of those games where each man/woman is for himself/herself, so you are really just competing against yourself as opposed to group games, which can just get crazy at times. I think this is the perfect game to play for hours and mix things up. Buy it and take it to your next game night. It's sure to be a hit!
title: Will you make the tower fall?

author: Monty
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on November 19, 2018
review_content: Do yourself a favor and pay a little more for the set in the tin box. The paperbox set is so annoying and flimsy after each use. It keeps opening up and the blocks keep falling out. You cant shove the pieces in quickly because if you do, they all wont fit. You have to take time to build the tower in the box which doesn't seem like a big deal until you have to do it multiple times.  Seriously. Buy the set in the tin box.
title: Buy the set with the tin box

author: Lee DeWald
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on January 3, 2002
review_content: "Jenga" is one of those games that, no matter how many times you play it, never gets old.  Each game is entirely different from the previous one, and becoming obsessed with being able to stack those little wooden blocks as high as you can is not uncommon.  As the stack reaches higher and higher, so do your nerves.Fun: This game is a lot of fun.  You haven't seen someone sweat until you've played "Jenga."  You know how hard it is to keep your hand steady when you know that one wrong move could send the entire tower of blocks crashing to the floor?  Talk about pressure.  Some blocks are smooth; some blocks are rough.  Trying to figure out which blocks to move (and when) only increases the fun factor.Educational Value: Not much in this case.  If you're looking for something to help you with your stacking or balancing skills, this could be the game for you.  This game also teaches you how to play with a delicate touch; get too rough, and your sky-scraper of blocks will consider you a pushover.Durability: I seriously doubt you're going to be able to break this game.  Not unless you've got a buzz saw handy.  This game is very durable; no matter how many times your wooden blocks crash to the floor, they will not break.  If you're looking for a game that will last for a LONG TIME, "Jenga" is right up your alley."Jenga" can be played all by yourself or with friends.  Both are great ways to play it, although playing with the blocks is most fun with others.  The interaction with other people especially makes it a winner; people who appear to be sturdy as a rock may not be as confident as they seem when you set this game in front of them.  Nobody I know has been able to keep a cool head when the tower of blocks begins to sway . . . and then CRASH!!Funny stuff.  I highly recommend this game.
title: "If you can't stack, prepare to step back!"

author: counselor
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on February 25, 2020
review_content: Great game that needs no cords, connectors with the right ends, plugs, or anything but a willingness to sit down for great fun & lots of laughs. The stacking sleeve so many have complained about is unnecessary. We only used it to get the pieces back in the box quicker! it evens the playing field for all ages. You never know who's going to win!
title: All ages can play together for lots of fun & laughter!

author: AA
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on April 7, 2005
review_content: In this era of mobile PSPs, x-boxes and gamecubes, a classic game like Jenga not only continues to survive, but thrive!My first experience was with my 2 nieces. I had never seen them before and since it always snows in MI, we couldn't go out. To break the awkward silence and pass time, my 4 year old pulled this tower of fun out. For next several hours we played this awsome game and bonded with each other. It was most fun I had with kids.Ok, now the specifics. The game works by first arranging all pieces to make a tower and then making each person pull out one piece at a time and put it on the top of the tower. Simple huh?Well as I said it is easy to learn but the idea is to select a piece that can be pulled out without causing a collapse and this is where men are separated from boys (and boys usually win!).You can actually learn to strategize your game and pull each piece in a sequence to make your tower taller.Each piece is made of wood and has the right size, finish and weight to support quite a bit of weight.If you are looking for a game that doesn't entail mindless button pushing or shooting those ugly monstors on tv screen, go for this one. Your kids will love it and hopefully you too!
title: Easy to learn, hard to master!!!

author: Amazon Customer
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on August 4, 2016
review_content: I bought this as a gift for a friend. She received and opened it only to find that the box was crawling with wood termites. I am utterly mortified and disgusted by this. I can't believe that I paid to send a bunch of termites to my friend as a gift. I immediately advised my friend to throw out the box to avoid any possibility of the termites spreading in her apartment or damaging her wooden floor. I cannot fathom how the manufacturer does not treat the wood to avoid this kind of calamity from occurring. I cannot even process a replacement or refund since the process requires that I ask my friend to pack up a box full of termites and send it back. I'm really quite disgusted by this whole affair.
title: Box of wood termites

author: apoem
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on May 26, 2002
review_content: Basically you take a block from the stack and then place it on the top. As you take blocks from the stack, the chances of having a collapse become higher.This is a fun game.We have put a few twists on it due to my two year old deciding he wanted to play with us. One way we play is we devide the blocks out and just start stacking with one block at a time. With my clumsy hands and a two year old (almost three) we quickly run into problems and the challenge becomes harder. Very fun. Another way we play is we take one from the stack but we don't place it on top, we stick it in our own pile. Whoever has the most blocks when the tower collapses wins.It is fun the way you are supposed to play it as well. We just made these other ways up as we went along with our kiddos.I like games that inspire creativity. I like that we can play it a different way and enable it to become a whole family affair instead of just a game for adults that the kids watch. This is a great game for younger children because they like watching the blocks fall. When we play we tie counting into it and talk about why the blocks fall (gravity), why they are loose and so on. IT is great for pre readers because it is developing eye and hand coordination.Enjoy.
title: An exciting, challenging game

Customer service is great also. I did have an issue with the staw falling out and they sent me a new top! I love the way you can tilt the bottle and just sip from the top without the water leaking out!! Love it!

author: Amazon Customer
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on December 22, 2004
review_content: Chenga is a great game for the whole family.  Any family member old enough to understand the idea of trying not to knock down the tower is old enough to play, which usually means anyone over three.  There is a good deal of skill for children to learn about being slow, calm, and careful when pulling and placing pieces, which makes this game very educational, at least in the sense of learning self-mastery.  The game is also fun and suspenseful, as each time someone takes a turn, everyone hold their breath a little while they wait to see if the tower will fall.  A super-nice feature of Chenga is that it allows the entire family to play the same game, without subjecting older members to silly baby games like Candy Land (which is nice, but gets old).  And best of all, Chenga is great value for money.  This is a game that doesn't cost much to begin with, is super-durable (almost impossible to break), and is unlikely to be out-grown at any time.
title: Great for the whole family

You attempt to get as many logs as possible without knocking down the tower…the last person playing when it falls, loses!  Sounds easy, doesn't it?  Some logs are much more difficult to move than others!  LOTS of fun!  We highly recommend this game!

author: D. M. Farmbrough
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on November 26, 2002
review_content: Jenga is great fun, as long as you have the right number and the right type of people to play it with. It is a twist on the classic Jack Straws game, where one item has to be removed without the stack collapsing. The difference with Jenga is that the removed wooden brick then has to be placed on top of the pile! The degree of dexterity involved means this isn't suitable for the under 5s, but other than that its appeal is very wide. The blocks are durable and the game is easy to pack away and set up. You might get bored with it if you have too many players as you have a long wait for your turn, but three or four people is the ideal. Recommended.
